Unique values of each variable

Since we have multiple years and panel regression is too complicated to implement here. We are less interested in the trend of whether race or gender would impact the probability of getting a warning/citation. So in order to simplify the issue, I will select the most recent year that has relative large amount of data points, which is 2015 according to the sorted table below.

Change categorical variables to binary

To further prepare for the logistic regression for the cross-sectional data in 2015, we change the “Yes” and “No” responses to 1 and 0, respectively.

library(dplyr)
TV2 <- mutate(TV_Y2015, vio_type_citation = ifelse(Violation.Type == "Citation", 1, 0)) %>%
       mutate(vio_type_warning = ifelse(Violation.Type == "Warning", 1, 0)) %>%
       mutate(vio_type_SERO = ifelse(Violation.Type == "SERO", 1, 0)) %>%
       mutate(vio_type_ESERO = ifelse(Violation.Type == "ESERO", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Male = ifelse(Gender == "M", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Female = ifelse(Gender == "F", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Alcohol = ifelse(Alcohol == "Yes", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Belts = ifelse(Belts == "Yes", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Black = ifelse(Race == "BLACK", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(White = ifelse(Race == "WHITE", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Hispanic = ifelse(Race == "HISPANIC", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Asian = ifelse(Race == "ASIAN", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Native_American = ifelse(Race == "NATIVE AMERICAN", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Other_race = ifelse(Race == "OTHER", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Personal.Injury = ifelse(Personal.Injury == "Yes", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Property.Damage = ifelse(Property.Damage == "Yes", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Fatal = ifelse(Fatal == "Yes", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Commercial.License = ifelse(Commercial.License == "Yes", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Commercial.Vehicle = ifelse(Commercial.Vehicle == "Yes", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(HAZMAT = ifelse(HAZMAT == "Yes", 1, 0))%>%
       mutate(Work.Zone = ifelse(Work.Zone == "Yes", 1, 0))

Cluster at location level and change binary to ratio variables.

According to Kaggle website (https://www.kaggle.com/rounak041993/traffic-violations-in-maryland-county), location of the violation is usually an address or intersection. There are in total 15,646 locations in the data in year 2015, which ensures we have enough data points to run regression after clustering.

length(unique(TV2$Location))
## [1] 15646
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29255473/most-frequent-value-mode-by-group
Mode <- function(x) {
  ux <- unique(x)
  ux[which.max(tabulate(match(x, ux)))]
}

TV3 <- TV2 %>%
select(Location, Belts, Alcohol, Male, Female, Personal.Injury, Property.Damage, Fatal, Commercial.License, Commercial.Vehicle, HAZMAT, vio_type_citation, vio_type_warning, vio_type_SERO, vio_type_ESERO, Black, White, Hispanic, Asian, Native_American, Other_race, Work.Zone, SubAgency) %>%
group_by(Location) %>%
summarise( Belts = sum(Belts)/n(), Alcohol = sum(Alcohol)/n(), 
           Personal.Injury = sum(Personal.Injury)/n(), 
           Property.Damage = sum(Property.Damage)/n(), 
           Fatal = sum(Fatal)/n(), 
           Commercial.License = sum(Commercial.License)/n(), 
           Commercial.Vehicle = sum(Commercial.Vehicle)/n(), 
           HAZMAT = sum(HAZMAT)/n(), 
           vio_type_warning = sum(vio_type_warning)/n(), 
           vio_type_ESERO = sum(vio_type_ESERO)/n(), 
           vio_type_SERO = sum(vio_type_SERO)/n(), 
           vio_type_citation = sum(vio_type_citation)/n(), 
           Black = sum(Black)/n(), White = sum(White)/n(), 
           Hispanic = sum(Hispanic)/n(), 
           Native_American = sum(Native_American)/n(), 
           Asian = sum(Asian)/n(), 
           Other_race = sum(Other_race)/n(), 
           Work.Zone = sum(Work.Zone)/n(), 
           Male = sum(Male)/n(), 
           Female = 1-Male,
           not_warning = 1 - vio_type_warning,
           not_citation = 1 - vio_type_citation,
           not_ESERO = 1 - vio_type_ESERO,
           not_SERO = 1 - vio_type_SERO,
           SubAgency = Mode(SubAgency))

Chi-squared tests

Null hypothesis (H0): the violation type and race are independent. Alternative hypothesis (H1): the violation type and race are dependent

library(reshape2)
# https://rpubs.com/biomanoos/balloonplot
contingency_tbl <- data.frame(cro(TV4$Violation.Type, list(TV4$Race)))
contingency_tbl <- contingency_tbl[1:4,]
Violation_type <- c("Citation","ESERO","SERO","Warning")
contingency_tbl['Violation_Type'] <- Violation_type
contingency_tbl <- contingency_tbl[,2:8]
contingency_tbl <- contingency_tbl[c(7,1:6)]
# Delete row 3 since it contains NAs (if I replace it with 0 the chi-square test will through an error)
contingency_tbl <- contingency_tbl[c(1,2,4),]
contingency_tbl 
##   Violation_Type ASIAN BLACK HISPANIC NATIVE.AMERICAN OTHER WHITE
## 1       Citation  1264  6259     3272              41  1241  6676
## 2          ESERO    65   214      190               5    29   230
## 4        Warning  2068  6764     3372              69  1722  9961
matrix_con <- as.matrix(contingency_tbl[2:7])
matrix_con
##   ASIAN BLACK HISPANIC NATIVE.AMERICAN OTHER WHITE
## 1  1264  6259     3272              41  1241  6676
## 2    65   214      190               5    29   230
## 4  2068  6764     3372              69  1722  9961
chisq.test(matrix_con)

## incorrect
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  matrix_con
## X-squared = 394.74, df = 10, p-value < 2.2e-16

As we can see above, the p-value is very low (well below 0.01), so we reject the null hypothses. In ohter words, the violation type and race are dependent.

Logistic Regressions

In order to assess the impact of race and gender on the probability of receiving a warning, we regress the binary variable vio_type_warning (1: received a warning; 0: did not receive a warning) on the set of independent variables after deleting those which have a large vif score. I only display the final regression here, please refer to the appendix of this html file to see other regressions tested before the final one.

In order for the regression coefficient to be unbiased estimates, we assume that there are no omitted variable bias, which implies we’ve included all the relevent variables in our model. I know this assumption may not be true, but due to limited data, we can assume it is true for now and interpret the coefficient under such assumption.

From the regression above, we can observe that our baseline group is white male, whose probability of receiving a warning is captured in the intercept term. All the coefficients should be interpreted as the natural log of odds of receiving a warning. Below is a chart of translating logodds to probability of receiving a warning (https://stats.idre.ucla.edu/other/mult-pkg/faq/general/faq-how-do-i-interpret-odds-ratios-in-logistic-regression/):

A positive logodds coefficient means the group is more likely to get a warning versus not getting a warning. Within the significant coefficients, we can see that white male and female are more likely to get a warning versus not, while being black and hispanic would be less likely to get a warning.

Here the dependent variable chanes from violation type citation to violation type warning, which is also binary.
